Having regard to the Treaty establishing the European Economic Community,
Having regard to Council Regulation (EEC) No 3796/81 of 29 December 1981 on the common organization of the market in fishery products (1) and, in particular, Article 24 (2) thereof,
Whereas the French Republic has requested the Commission to take measures to suspend imports into France of yellowfin tuna intended for the industrial manufacture of products falling within heading No 16.04 of the Common Customs Tariff; whereas the Commission has requested further information, which was supplied on 8 November 1985;
Whereas the volume of the imports of the product in question into France between the beginning of 1985 and 15 October this year, which shows a 20 % increase compared with the same period of last year, and the price levels at which the said imports have been made, especially in recent months, have had an impact on the level of selling prices on the French market for yellowfin tuna in its most common presentation;
Whereas the stocks of yellowfin tuna available in certain third countries are very large and the price levels at which such stocks are offered on the international market are very few;
Whereas Community production of yellowfin tuna intended for industrial manufacture is concentrated in France; whereas the said Member State also possesses a large tuna-processing industry which traditionally obtains a large part of its supplies on the international market;
Whereas, in order to prevent any distrubance of the French yellowfin tuna market such as to jeopardize the aims of Article 39 of the Treaty, detailed advance knowledge is needed of the conditions relating to any imports of the product in question into France; whereas a system for the surveillance of French imports of yellowfin tuna intended for the industrial manufacture of products falling within heading No 16.04 of the Common Customs Tariff should therefore be introduced for a limited period;
Whereas, according to the information currently available, no such situation warranting special measures obtains on the markets of the other regions of the Community; whereas the surveillance system should therefore be confined to imports into France;
